00:02:25.700 --> 00:02:29.310
So for people that are not programmers, when we talk about

00:02:29.310 --> 00:02:32.090
packages, imagine if we would like to, for the ad

00:02:32.660 --> 00:02:37.840
protocol, we would like to see the display name.

00:02:37.840 --> 00:02:40.860
Blue Sky app has a nice public API for it.

00:02:40.860 --> 00:02:43.220
But we normally don't start from scratch.

00:02:43.220 --> 00:02:46.530
We use libraries that are distributed as packages.

00:02:46.600 --> 00:02:49.800
So in JavaScript, we will import it.

00:02:49.800 --> 00:02:52.760
A client, for example, from adq, from Marie

00:02:52.760 --> 00:02:53.060
.

00:02:53.060 --> 00:02:57.760
And we can create a client for that service.

00:02:57.760 --> 00:03:01.860
And this let us do very comfortable with type it, like

00:03:01.860 --> 00:03:06.810
functions, and get the display name in an easy way.

00:03:06.860 --> 00:03:10.630
So packages let us build software collaboratively, and depending on

00:03:10.670 --> 00:03:12.880
the work of amazing other people.

00:03:12.880 --> 00:03:15.340
And don't start from scratch.

00:03:15.340 --> 00:03:19.360
The package registry from the web, like the JavaScript, is

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:20.140
NPM.

00:03:20.140 --> 00:03:23.140
You will do NPM install a client to get this one

00:03:23.140 --> 00:03:25.020
in your project.

00:03:25.020 --> 00:03:27.900
And in NPMX, we actually have a dependency on

00:03:27.960 --> 00:03:28.580
Marie.

00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:30.640
Like, we are using her libraries.

00:03:30.640 --> 00:03:31.960
So thanks, Marie.

00:03:32.020 --> 00:03:35.900
Not only on Marie, but on a lot of really wonderful

00:03:35.900 --> 00:03:37.320
open source projects.

00:03:37.320 --> 00:03:39.580
All the beta stack, NACs, Vue,

00:03:39.580 --> 00:03:41.480
and JS org.

00:03:41.480 --> 00:03:43.640
Like, there is so many people.

00:03:43.640 --> 00:03:47.350
We couldn't have built NPMX without this in two

00:03:47.350 --> 00:03:48.280
months.

00:03:48.280 --> 00:03:51.510
We are relying on all this, the work of a lot

00:03:51.510 --> 00:03:52.520
of people.

00:03:52.520 --> 00:03:55.540
And in the case of NPM, so this is the

00:03:55.540 --> 00:03:57.310
world largest software registry.

00:03:57.320 --> 00:03:59.460
This is a graph from, like, Github released

00:03:59.460 --> 00:04:00.630
it not long ago.

00:04:00.700 --> 00:04:03.390
If you take into account JavaScript and TypeScript together, it

00:04:03.390 --> 00:04:05.080
's like almost double of Python.

00:04:05.080 --> 00:04:11.140
It is an amazing registry of the work of so many people

00:04:11.260 --> 00:04:11.640
.

00:04:11.640 --> 00:04:14.820
And it's a little bit hard to understand, because it

00:04:15.030 --> 00:04:16.640
consists of three parts.

00:04:16.640 --> 00:04:19.320
The registry is called NPM and has that logo.

00:04:19.320 --> 00:04:21.640
The CLI is called NPM and has that logo.

00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:23.840
And the website is called npmjs.

00:04:23.840 --> 00:04:25.480
com and has the same logo.

00:04:25.480 --> 00:04:28.000
So people, when they think about NPM, they think

00:04:28.060 --> 00:04:29.720
about all the things together.

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:31.210
But there are three different parts.

00:04:31.260 --> 00:04:34.300
Like, the registry where all the tarballs are stored,

00:04:34.300 --> 00:04:36.640
and they have, like, a public API that you can

00:04:36.640 --> 00:04:37.180
fetch.

00:04:37.180 --> 00:04:39.450
The CLI is something, the command line interface that we

00:04:39.450 --> 00:04:42.220
use to interact with that registry.

00:04:42.220 --> 00:04:46.670
And the website allow us to browse, search, like,

00:04:46.680 --> 00:04:48.060
do admin stuff.

00:04:48.060 --> 00:04:50.940
So NPM, right now, it is on the hands

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:52.330
of Microsoft.

00:04:52.340 --> 00:04:57.730
And yeah, they have not been adding a lot of features

00:04:57.860 --> 00:04:59.290
lately to it.

00:04:59.420 --> 00:05:03.450
So other open source people and, like, projects have been

00:05:03.650 --> 00:05:06.740
trying to say, maybe we should innovate a little bit.

00:05:06.740 --> 00:05:10.290
And so on the registry side, you have JSR from

00:05:10.290 --> 00:05:11.880
the Deno Fox.

00:05:11.880 --> 00:05:15.860
You have Vault that also were ex-NPM Fox,

00:05:15.860 --> 00:05:18.380
trying to see, like, what they could improve.

00:05:18.400 --> 00:05:23.060
Like, we could have, like, twice maybe as fast

00:05:23.060 --> 00:05:25.720
if we are able to modify the server and, like,

00:05:25.860 --> 00:05:28.860
make the CLI and the server together communicate in a little

00:05:28.910 --> 00:05:30.320
bit better way.

00:05:30.360 --> 00:05:33.140
On the CLI, this has been for a long time

00:05:33.140 --> 00:05:33.440
.

00:05:33.440 --> 00:05:36.320
YARN first showed a lot of innovation.

00:05:36.320 --> 00:05:40.580
Then PMPM in the ecosystem.

00:05:40.580 --> 00:05:42.940
And from then, now PMPM is huge.

00:05:42.940 --> 00:05:45.400
We are all using PMPM.

00:05:45.400 --> 00:05:50.780
And on the website side, we have nothing.

00:05:50.960 --> 00:05:53.460
Actually, there are some things, for example, for the

00:05:53.460 --> 00:05:56.600
graph, there is a lot of mini websites to do graph

00:05:56.600 --> 00:05:58.030
, for the little graphs.

00:05:58.040 --> 00:05:59.840
And they are, like, all YARN, JS

00:05:59.840 --> 00:06:03.120
R, Bolt, all have their own little browsers.

00:06:03.180 --> 00:06:06.130
But there's nothing that is, like, we can put

00:06:06.130 --> 00:06:07.020
here.

00:06:07.020 --> 00:06:09.760
And we actually need something there.

00:06:09.770 --> 00:06:12.420
Because I don't know if you see how the light in

00:06:12.420 --> 00:06:13.100
the room changed it.

00:06:13.100 --> 00:06:16.880
But it only has light mode.

00:06:16.880 --> 00:06:20.910
So for some of us, that is why we don't

00:06:20.910 --> 00:06:22.000
use it.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:25.720
And also, like, if you see the little weekly downloads

00:06:25.720 --> 00:06:28.360
graph there, you can only see the last week.

00:06:28.360 --> 00:06:30.840
You cannot, like, explore the graph.

00:06:30.840 --> 00:06:33.010
There is so much more that we could do here.

00:06:33.020 --> 00:06:36.850
And, like, the packages and all the relationships, it

00:06:36.850 --> 00:06:38.150
is a social endeavor.

00:06:38.180 --> 00:06:41.490
Like, we could see where are the maintainers?

00:06:41.560 --> 00:06:43.400
Where are the-- I don't know where there are the

00:06:43.670 --> 00:06:44.400
